<subSubSection id="C30F10975C13FFFEFF52FBE8FB78F6B1" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="8BAA431C5C13FFFEFF52FBE8FE9EF603" blockId="3.[189,310,1114,1140]" box="[189,310,1114,1140]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
<heading id="D0E2F4705C13FFFEFF52FBE8FE9EF603" bold="true" box="[189,310,1114,1140]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" reason="3">
<emphasis id="B9619F0E5C13FFFEFF52FBE8FE9EF603" bold="true" box="[189,310,1114,1140]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">Diagnosis</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BAA431C5C13FFFEFF52FB3AFB78F6B1" blockId="3.[189,1398,1160,1222]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">The new species is characterized by the shapes of the male epiproct and genitalia. Male epiproct pentagonal with concave posterior margin and dorsal sclerite of male genitalia stilliform.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C30F10975C13FFFEFF52FB5FFE5FF72E" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="8BAA431C5C13FFFEFF52FB5FFEECF770" blockId="3.[189,324,1261,1287]" box="[189,324,1261,1287]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
<heading id="D0E2F4705C13FFFEFF52FB5FFEECF770" bold="true" box="[189,324,1261,1287]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" reason="3">
<emphasis id="B9619F0E5C13FFFEFF52FB5FFEECF770" bold="true" box="[189,324,1261,1287]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">Etymology</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BAA431C5C13FFFEFF52FAAEFE5FF72E" blockId="3.[189,1398,1308,1369]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
The name of the new species derives from the Greek word ‘ 
<emphasis id="B9619F0E5C13FFFEFC66FAAFFC14F741" box="[905,956,1309,1334]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">pent</emphasis>
’ (‘pentagonal’), referring to the male epiproct being pentagonal.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
